Goal (simple)

Create a GitHub repository, initialize a local git repo, commit a README, push to GitHub, and verify history. This builds the core habit: commit + push + clear messages.

Quick checklist (do in order)

Install Git (if not installed)

Configure your name & email

Create local project folder + README

Initialize git, add, commit

Create GitHub repo (UI) or via gh (optional)

Add remote, push (first push sets upstream)

Verify on GitHub and check commit log locally

Commands & exact steps (Linux / macOS — adapt for Windows PowerShell)
1) Install Git

Ubuntu / Debian:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y git


macOS (Homebrew):

brew install git


Verify

git --version
# Expect something like: git version 2.x.x

2) Configure identity (one-time)
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "you@example.com"


Check:

git config --list

3) Make project folder and README
mkdir ~/devops-practice-day1
cd ~/devops-practice-day1
cat > README.md <<'EOF'
# DevOps Practice — Day 1

Task: Git basics — initialize repo, commit README, push to GitHub.

Notes:
- Commands used:
  - git init
  - git add README.md
  - git commit -m "chore: add README for Day 1"
  - git branch -M main
  - git remote add origin <remote-url>
  - git push -u origin main
EOF

4) Initialize repo, add, commit
git init
git add README.md
git commit -m "chore(day1): add README for Day 1 — Git basics"


Verify log:

git log --oneline
# Should show your commit

5) Create GitHub repo (two ways)

A — Using GitHub web UI (simplest):

Go to GitHub → New repository → name: devops-practice-day1 → Public or Private → Create repository.

On the page you’ll see the git remote add origin ... and push commands.

B — Using GitHub CLI (gh) (optional):

# install gh if not present (see gh docs), then:
gh auth login           # follow prompts to authenticate
gh repo create devops-practice-day1 --public --source=. --remote=origin --push
# this will create and push automatically

6) Add remote & push (if using web UI)

Copy the remote URL from GitHub (HTTPS or SSH). Example (HTTPS):

git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/<your-username>/devops-practice-day1.git
git push -u origin main


If using SSH and you don't have keys:

ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "you@example.com"
# Accept defaults, optionally passphrase
cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub   # copy this
# Add key to GitHub → Settings → SSH and GPG keys → New SSH key
# Then push using SSH remote:
git remote set-url origin git@github.com:<your-username>/devops-practice-day1.git
git push -u origin main

7) Verify

On local:

git status
git log --oneline
